caption: So excited that our neighborhood gem is back open for dine in. While we miss our happy hours at the bar watching Seki-san work his magic, the stepped-out-of-DC-and-into-Tokyo feel is still there. Plus I could eat their kalbi and potato salad for every meal. Can also confirm that their takeout holds up, and is very carefully (beautifully even?) packaged to go.
No one else was really there so I was comfortable eating w/o a mask on. Wine and sushi were both amazing!

I'm really sad about this. I'd been dying to check out this Izakaya because I love Japanese bars and having studied Japanese most of my life and lived in the country, I just love Izakayas. I take a date there. We wait to sit and our waiter takes our app and drink order, tries to take our drink menu after we say we'll hold on to it. He was like "I can bring it back!" If they had very few menus, he could have said "this is our only drink menu" or something other than arguing w me when I didn't know anything was wrong.  That was the least of it. He came back to the table only a few times. Once  to notify me that there was an English side of the menu. I was looking at the Japanese side reading it, and maybe he thought I was dumb and couldn't turn a menu over. Like Maybe he thought I was about to complain about foreign words, but I hadn't, I didn't, I wouldn't. He really did tell me at least three times I didn't have to read the Japanese side. Then he swung by again to correct my Japanese.(this guy is not Japanese himself no matter his language proficiency. So we're both non-Japanese.) He did it again a second later when he finally asked us if wanted anything and proceeded to judge all the questions I was asking. And out right refused to order  something I didn't even order yet.  The food we did order was great. They menu was limited, sake selection is good...but who wants to eat any food while being gaslight by an angry waiter? I guess he made enough money that night or he hates women. I won't go back.

Izakaya Seki is a great restaurant, period. Their sashimi is perfectly prepared and well sourced, and their cooked dishes reflect equal care and quality.  Take out is available, and the quality doesn't suffer because of care and ingenuity - the onigiri wrapping is nothing short of amazing.  Try, and enjoy.
"Unbelievable food, lovely service, great setting and atmosphere."
Japanese food, so great. The service was very kind and attentive. The place has a nice feel to it.
Fresh, delicious and wonderful food.
The pork belly and tofu are unbelievable. Everything else is great too!
Nice atmosphere and very attentive service. The menu was fresh and delicious. Will surely recommend this spot to friends and family. Convenient prices and large meals. Great work.
The bento box that Izakaya Seki are doing during covid was so great. Very authentic mix of noodles, rice, vegetables, chicken karrage and more. Great value and service when we picked it up.

This is definitely the most authentic Japanese restaurant that I've found in DC. After living in Japan for 2 years, I've been looking for a place that was even a little similar to a real Japanese restaurant and I loved this place!
This place is amazing. The food is very good. Small place. Make sure to have a reservation.

(Translated by Google) Satisfied with cooking, comfort and customer service. It is a shop that I want to visit again soon.  I arrived a little later than the reservation time, but accepted the heart bath. The sashimi, skewers, deep-fried food, and boiled food were all delicious and satisfying.  (Original) 料理、居心地、接客全てに満足。 すぐまた訪れたいお店です。  予約時間より少し遅れて到着しましたが、心浴受け入れてくださいました。 料理はお刺身、串物、揚げ物、煮物全て美味しく大満足、日本酒も頂き夢心地でしたください
I love coming here the staff is so attentive and have awesome recommendations on food if you never been here before, the food taste amazing and very fresh.
This place is amazing, if you want absolutely amazing Japanese food come by and enjoy. Fresh produce and real skill, come here whenever I do enough overtime to justify it :’)
The best.
The waitress who took our order was really unfriendly. She did not even took our order and dismiss us.
Delicious food and great vibe!

The first authentic Japanese izakaya experience I have found in the mid-Atlantic. The food is amazing, the staff friendly and helpful, and the environment is cozy and chic. Their shochu menu is the best in the area and bottle keep service is available. Those looking for an authentic experience should note that this is where Japanese celebrities and bands have been known to come for a taste of home when visiting DC.

(Translated by Google) The fish smells a lot fishy and the amount is very small. I had three foods alone, but I was not full. Good value for money and no food taste.  (Original) 해산물에서 비린내가 많이나고, 양이 무척 적다. 혼자 음식 세개를 시켰는데도 배가 부르지 않았다. 가성비 나쁘고 음식 맛이 없는 곳.

(Translated by Google) Very good Japanese, the sashimi are ultra fresh and the tempura excellent. No frills everything is in the plate, very good authentic dishes as in Japan. Superb choice of sake  (Original) Très bon japonais, les sashimis sont ultra frais et les tempuras excellentes. Pas de fioritures tout est dans l’assiette, de très bon plats authentiques comme au japon. Superbe choix de Saké

Get here now! Opens at 5. So fresh and authentic. The warmest welcome. Sashimi? Just ask for the chef’s choice. Nothing here that is less than exquisite. The beer is so fresh and cold. Enjoy meat, veggies or all of the above!
Excellent! Expensive because each plate is small and you need many. It comes out to about $60 a person with no drinks. Good food, cool little spot just a little bit expensive for what you get.
Incredibly quick service, very friendly staff, pleasant atmosphere and delicious food
To compare it to a normal Japanese bento would be putting it nicely.Don't ho here if you want good Japanese food.

Oishii 美味しい  Ignore the very few negative reviews. Go to Izakaya Seki early enough to get a seat, and go with humility, respect, curiosity, and openness and you’ll have a great dinner. Taishō runs a tight ship, and it shows in the care and attention you’ll find in the best dishes. Can’t wait to go back.
The store is small, the service attitude is poor, the food materials are general, not Japanese food, the sea urchin quality is poor, not worth trying, it is a shame for Japanese food.
Tuna/Salmon Sashimi was 6/10. Kaarage was 6/10. Chicken meatballs HIGH sodium. Buttered mushrooms HiGH sodium. Service was worse than the food.

Food is good but service is poor. I really want to give them a better rating but they have done something obnoxious every time I have been there.  And I have given them a few tries already. They should improve service - they are not as good as they think they are.

The portions were delicious, but small and I left a bit hungry. I don't feel like I got my money's worth overall. I would suggest they serve a bowl of rice with the sashimi, that would have balanced it out nicely.
Possibly the best sushi in DC

Absolutleu delicious meal.  The sashimi had a variety of different textures and flavors that all tasted great. The scallop melted like butter in my mouth.  Whatever you order will definitely be amazing, but definitely try out the crab croquettes.
Astonishingly quick service.

Cool atmosphere, the room is essentially one long counter. I had the best salmon sashimi I’ve had in the city at this place! Also, they have quite the wide range on their menti and the staff are attentive and happy to explain and recommend items. Service was very fast as well, my sushi and rice ball came out to me within minutes. Will definitely go back
Portions are for sharing that add up fast.
One of the most authentic Japanese bar in DC, not super pricy, if u like sashimi/ japanese grill u should definitely try this one.
My go to Japanese spot! All good and on the quick. A very lovely assortment of Japanese beers.

I came here with a good number of friends and thoroughly enjoyed the food. Expect to order 3 plates per person and be sure to share. The beef ribs and full squid were particularly memorable. Staff was helpful in recommending dishes and was able to offer new dishes based on the initial round of plates that we enjoyed.

(Translated by Google) Assorted sashimi, Obanzai, all delicious. The atmosphere was good and the service was pleasant and polite, making it a great dinner. Especially, sashimi is fresh and thick, so it is highly satisfying.  (Original) 刺身盛合せ、おばんざい、どれも美味しくいただきました。雰囲気も良く、サービスも気持ちが良いくらい丁寧で、最高のディナーになりました。特に刺身は鮮度良く、更に厚切りなので、満足感が高いです。
Preparation is what you’re paying for. The food overall was ok, short rib and tuna was very good though

Great service. Average food. Tastes like what I imagine my take on Japanese soulfood would be. Overpriced for what it was-. The sable fish was fine. I spent $70 for potato salad and subpar pickles, one piece of acceptable sable fish, and a carafe of sake. I’m still hungry and annoyed that I paid that much to only go somewhere else after.
Best sushi ever 😍
A terrific, if not inexpensive, Japanese restaurant. Good sashimi, wonderful vegetables, lots of selection in the sake and shochu available...a classic izakaya. Lovely, simple, open late-ish.

I and my wife went to DC for the run-away weekend. I have stayed in Tokyo for 3 years and I had to say the food is just average STREET FOOD level and taste, with over marked price. The uni was not sweet at all, taste bland. I don’t want to be rude, but I don’t get the point of people who give a five stars on the food, seriously. I realized we left the credit card on the dining table,  We called millions times and no one reply. My wife google it and told me the restaurant doesn’t have a cell phone, they can only be contacted by email. She emailed them, never reply.  Fine!!! I don’t know if the owner gonna check this message, but could you give me an idea about the extra tips? The food is $111.65 ( we don’t order any alcohol at all) , I pay $130 which more than 15% tips. I am working on get my new credit card from the bank, so I check the transaction record. Why do you charge $131.65? I don’t mind $1.65 , but you can’t charge whatever you want to, right? I’m back to NY and What should I do now? Call you? Oh you don’t have phone in 21th century. Well done, Seki!
Vegi trio was delicious

If you have eaten here recently,  ***check your bank statement***.  Avoid this place if you have ever been to an izakaya in Japan.  Food was average at best and the service was horrible by Japanese standards.  If you eat here, check your bank account after your visit.  On top of the $120 bill, I was charged another $158.  ****Email has been sent to the owner**** I will update my review as needed.

We thought we arrived early enough to avoid the wait and it turned out others were even earlier. Lucky enough we got two seats at the counter.  Our server Daniel took our 6-dish order by memorizing them without bother to write them down, perfect memory.  Hamachi Kama (fish cheek, grilled) A+ Saba, marinated A- Whole squid A Obanzai A- Kushi Katsu (fried pork belly) A Smelt B  Service was friendly and extremely efficient.  The ambient was acceptable for an Izakaya.  We both regard the food as authentic and of good quality. Fishes were very fresh.
Sashimi was not very clean and fresh. It taste like refrigerator.

I finally got to go after having this place on my want-to-go list for over two years.  It was a warm and friendly atmosphere with fantastic food and homey touches.  I ordered the toro, Japanese omelette with eel, vegetable tempura, some calpico drink, ginger ice cream, peanut butter panna cotta... it was all great, I don't have a single negative thing to say.  Just look at the hand-drawn menus whose edges have worn down as happy eaters have poured through their pages.  This place loves food and wants you to love food too.

Have had a couple of amazing meals here and decided to leave them the 5 star review they deserve . Amazing place with great service and food that is always worth the trip. They are very attentive and the menu is filled with goodies.
Lovely food, beer pairings, super fresh vegetables and excellent service.  Never disappointed in a meal here.  Sometimes the upstairs can be a little loud b/c it is small.
So good!
Not worth the price. Every dish looks like appetizer, sashimis are not fresh.

The food is authentic and fresh. No to mention the drink menu. If you love sake then you must visit. However the food is not too much. They said the hot pot is for two but I finished all by myself, even order one extra rice ball.
I really enjoyed my experience here. Attentive service without being intrusive.  The food is amazing. One of my top ten restaurants in DC. I wish they took reservations for small parties.

This place is SO expensive. While this restaurant is certainly tasty, I just am not a fan of places where you spend $100 for two people and come away not fully satiated. Of the things we ordered, I thought the nabe, onigiri, veggie tempura to be worthwhile, but I thought several of the grilled seafood items to be quite pricy.
Just incredible.

This place is amazing in so many ways. They provide an interesting izakaya experience with great food. I used to really love it there. However, there is something off about their service. It’s not very japanese in a pure service sense. Specifically, there is one server who has a very aloof attitude. She has served me now 5-7 times and I’m so tired of her attitude that I won’t come back to the restaurant. The last time I came in and asked for a happy hour menu she said, “haven’t you already seen it? You’re a regular customer”. I said no. She then gave me the regular menu. I asked what the happy hour menu was and she said oh, you know the drinks and the poke dish with no price. I’m just so annoyed by her and one of the other server’s (who i think is an owner) poor service. Another time I came by and they insisted there were no seats for happy hour when there were seats available. She had to put me on a list, even though there were no customers using the seats. The whole thing is so un-japanese and unwelcoming. They act like it is a chore to allow someone to eat in the restaurant. Very hipster and too cool for you. If you are going to try the restaurant, don’t do it during happy hour. They haven’t seem to get how that works...

Always had a superb meal here. Very nice ‘home cooked’ Japanese meals are served here by the excellent chef. My Japanese (as well as non-Japanese) friends love coming here. Selection is great and menu varies often perhaps by season, but we always enjoy all the small dishes to share. Sake options are great too!
Amazing place with interesting and unique food as well as awesome staff

Authentic Japanese izakaya. The karaage is fantastic - a highlight of the meal - and the tuna nuta was also fresh and flavorful.  We received attentive, knowledgeable service and enjoyed the atmosphere.
Delicious authentic Japanese--not the typical Americanized kind--In an intimate minimalist space. Excellent service, too--Ellen did a wonderful job helping us choose our dishes.
Great taste. Nice servers.
Had a great experience there. Only about a 40min wait (went somewhere else to grab drinks). Good service, great food. I enjoyed having Japanese food that wasn’t just sushi.
Perfect fod, great environment! Would come again and recommand to my fellows. Would change the price rating to $$$

(Translated by Google) I love Seki. This place is by far the best in DMV. I had Sashimi 5, kushikatsu, obansai 3, crab and cream croquettes, and fried rice. Everything was so delicious. Especially, sashimi's quality was far beyond expectation.  It is the most delicious Japanese restaurant in DC. It is delicious what you eat, but the taste of sashimi is overwhelming.  (Original) I love Seki. This place is by far the best in DMV. I had Sashimi 5, kushikatsu, obansai 3, crab and cream croquettes, and fried rice. Everything was so delicious. Especially, sashimi’s quality was far beyond expectation.  DCで一番美味しい和食屋さんです。何を食べても美味しいですが、やはりお刺身の美味しさが圧倒的です。
Super good, super friendly. Elegant and cozy at the same time. Our favorite treat.
Great sake and shochu selection. Very authentic. Kanpachi was amazing
SO DELICIOUS.  Had the warm udon noodles and fritters.  Can't wait to go back!
Get the ara yaki
All dishes are real Japanese taste. I recommend.
Get the beef tongue
Our favorite place to being friends when they come into town. It's always great food and I love the semi-hidden location just off of U St.

One of the best meals I've ever had. Everything was so fresh and expertly executed. We had a mackerel dish (aji) which completely blew me away. The chef prepares the meat of the fish to eat raw, and then lightly fries what's left over, the head and tail. Absolutely delicious, I fully intend to come back next time I'm in DC.

Finally got to try Izakaya Seki after all these years! I don't know why it took us so long, but the boy and I have been wanting to try Izakaya Seki for the longest time and we finally got around to it this past week.  Since we came just under a hour before they were closing, there were plenty of seats. We chose to sit at the bar, since we like to watch the chefs cook.  We ordered: + Chutoro ($26) + Agedashi tofu ($7.50) + Mushrooms with butter and garlic ($12.50) + Ojiya soba ($10) + Inaniwa udon ($10) + Two rice balls (ume and konbu) at $3.50 each + Tsukune ($8)  What's great about Izakaya Seki is how the customer makes the experience unique - you can come here after work to grab a couple of dishes and some sake to unwind or you can impress a date with a variety of exotic and interesting plates. I enjoyed all of the dishes we ordered, although I was mildly disappointed by the udon. The broth was a little bit too salty, quite a shame because the dashi they make is very good. Noodles were very nice too. Inaniwa udon is hand-stretched, hand-kneaded, and slightly thinner than typical udon.  Great little spot for those craving authentic Japanese cuisine. Owner of Sushi Taro even comes here. It's a casual izakaya restaurant, so the atmosphere feels relaxed. Our service was fantastic, and we even got to chat with Cizuka Seki, who was behind the counter making everyone's food and is one half of the daughter-father team behind Izakaya Seki.
Authentic Japanese small plates that are of excellent quality and taste, and wide selection of Sake to go with the dishes
Omg! Authentic food just as you would find it in Japan.
Nice place, good food, very fair prices
Split between an intimate sit down restaurant on top amd a ramen bar on the ground floor. This place offers two great aspects of japanese dining

What a wonderful gem of a place in  DC. Everything we tasted was absolutely fantastic. Tried over 15 items from all over the menu and everything was delicious. Service was quick, staff friendly. Seating is limited so come early or be prepared to wait. But its well worth it.
I would not suggest the Sushi or Sashimi in this place. The hot good are good. Pricey.
Staff was rude. Limited, expensive menu

Underwhelming. I had huge expectations, but left feeling I could have had a better experience at another three or four Japanese restaurants in the DC area - foodwise. You know they are trying hard, but the dishes didn't meet the mark. I may try one more time, which is hard to do in this city with so many options.  Always feel free to reach out to me on Twitter @joerazz

Left empty in my wallet and in my stomach : So the food is alright.. I'm from out of state so the price seems very steep comparing to a few different factors Location: any place around is very hard to find parking, the restaurant itself is very casual but with a fancy restaurant price.  As I was very unhappy what made matters worse was.. The waiter could see I was not happy and never ever asked if everything was okay or if we liked the food.. I think this made mg experience here even worse.  Food: is alright.. You might not get full with a plate or two and each one is over $17 for most.. I didn't get quite full with a single tab of 35 dollars for two small plates. Total for two hungry people can go for around $95 for 5 small plates as recommendedby server.  Service: attentive, was alright but the place is so hard to get around with a very limited space.  Price: $$$  Something i really didn't like ( I was not explained) was that when you order.. Its not a main entre but separate dish so you and your partner might not eat at the same time as I finished my meal way before his arrived. ( again I was not awared not explained)  * plate sharing * not entre etc kind of place  Came for the squid which was $17 by itself ( no dishes included)  Overall food ratio to price ratio to location ratio is a 3 at most.
Excellent izakaya. Loved it.

We visited Izakaya Seki on our anniversary and it was a quiet night. While the service and atmosphere were excellent, food was just OK. I know this place is praised highly but my experience wasn't excellent enough to give 5 stars.
(Translated by Google) The service was great and the food was all delicious.  (Original) 接客が素晴らしく、料理も全て美味しかったです。
Great food. Authentic Japanese food.

Family unfriendly.  If you have small kids, go elsewhere.  They do not want you there.  Period.  Poor service, below mediocre food.  Out of the three items we ordered, one was undercooked (chicken so...), one item was forgotten, and the third was not edible.   Will never step my foot there, nor recommend to anyone.
Get the udon and rice balls with salmon at all costs
Good but expensive for what it is.
Great food

Delicious!  I love to go to this restaurant and take friends.  They source amazingly fresh fish and prepare it in a simple but delicious way.  If you sit at the bar downstairs prepare to be mesmerized by the preparation taking place in front of you.  Definitely a place to go to and then go back to try everything else!
in love with this tiny place.

Hands down the best Japanese food I've had stateside, outside of my late Obisan's (Japanese for Grandmother) kitchen. Already miss this place a few hours later. Super tiny restaurant, so get there early or wait, and you won't be disappointed. US Japanese cuisine is so riddled with "Steak Houses" and "Sushi Bars" but most people don't know that it's more than raw fish and Hibachi. This restaurant brought back memories of my trauma as a young kid with rice balls and cold noodle packed lunches in the best of ways. When you're young you think PB&Js are cool, but homestyle Japanese cuisine is where it's at when you're an adult, and I haven't found a place that does it better.
Really good Japanese food in a subtle restaurant
Best meal i've had in States, wide selection of sake. It's expensive though, and you may not be full even after a many courses.
Nice little place, the food is decent and just a little overpriced to me.
Somewhat Americanized izakaya. Only Sapporo on draft. Smaller sashimi sampler was just okay. Yakionigiri and yakitori didn't live up to our expectations.
Drools all around
Delicious food.

Cozy. Very good quality izakaya, pleasantly surprised by the freshness of the sashimi. Loved sitting at the counter. The fried oysters were juicy and crispy on the outside. It was entertaining watching the amazing coordination of the line cooks.
Tasty authentic Japanese tapas style food !!
Best Japanese in DC

Cozy venue next to the 930 Club. The inside is reminiscent of a Japanese tea house. Food is served in small plates (tapas like), and like tapas, without any flare or much presentation to it. Service is also unremarkable.  The wait staff were neither engaging or disparaging. Very good selection of Sake but this is not the main reason to come to any restaurant. Overpriced for an izakaya, which traditionally is a bar that serves a bit of food. You could leave with your wallet empty and still hungry. I would recommend they reduce the menue to 10 items or less and focus more on the sake or restructure the menu around the sake as a pairing.
We usually get the chef’s choice sashimi.
I loved the food here, the only thing little bit annoying u cant make reservation only for a big group
Very authentic. A must try.
This place is legit. Extremely good and fresh food. A wide variety of options and rotating specials means you can come here again and again and again be amazed.
The omakase is wonderful. Don't miss the tempura kisu and the fish collars.
Great sake program, felt more like the izakayas of Tokyo than most places, excellent sashimi and tasty yakitori!

Very nice family own restaurant. Felt like i was in Japan. With the amazing service and chef behind the bar, seeing how he cooks is like an performance arts at the theater.  Good place to visit if its your first time in the city for Japanese tapas style.
Expensive but extremely fresh!  HH is a $5 draft Sapporo with a small snack.  Small space, so don't bring a large group.
Intimate authentic Izakaya with everything going for it.
Order the BBC here it's so big and delicious 😉

Horrible, horrible, horrible.  You’ve been warned:  I’ve got an axe to grind here.  I ate here a few years ago and I'm still incredibly bitter about the travesty of a "dining experience" to which my friend and I were so tepidly treated.  I happened to be in DC and was eager to spend more than usual for a special meal for my friend and I at an authentic Japanese restaurant.  I was expecting izakaya dishes served with the precision and care of kaiseki in a refined, cordial, polite, warm, and inviting atmosphere, and what we got was just the opposite.  A self-absorbed art school dropout with a nasty superiority complex, animated by an unmistakable malice (and no doubt self-loathing), shot us cold daggers across the restaurant before frigidly intercepting us as we waited patiently at the threshold of this little slice of hell.  She told us to sit right where we were standing, at the far end of the wrap-around bar.  She then proceeded to reluctantly hand us our menus, as if in disbelief and ripe with indignation that she had to serve “our kind.“  The judgement in the air was palpable, and as it became ever-so clear, so was the pretension.  This place served dishes so refined, so elevated aesthetically and culinarily, that it seemed as though it must only, with profound regret, open its doors to the uncultured public at all.  As our lovely waitress left to fetch our water bowls (after all, we were essentially mangy mutts in her all-knowing eyes), we glanced over the scant and steeply priced izakaya-style menu of small dishes.  Quite a few things sounded appealing, and with the price tags I assumed the food must be of very high quality.  I decided amidst my anger and humiliation at being treated like garbage to try my best to placate the waitress so that my friend and I could enjoy the food they had to offer.  That was a tremendous mistake.  The food was very hit and miss, but overall decidedly mediocre, especially given the portions and prices.  The zaru soba was particularly disappointing in texture and presentation for a restaurant with such lofty self-esteem.  It was thrown down before me, in a messy un-manicured pile on a cheap plastic tray.  Needless to say this was far from the “kaiseki” I was expecting.  Some portion of meat I ordered (I can’t even recall what it was because my mind was overflowing with anger and disbelief) was not even edible because of the collagen was so dense… even after vigorously but discreetly chewing for at least over 60 seconds.  My friend tried the $18 dish of uni, but can’t comment on the quality as it’s the only time he’s tried it.  Don’t even get me started about the chef… he loves to give you lingering death stares.  It’s not a glance to see if you’re enjoying the food, but a stare to see if you’re even capable of appreciating it, and moreover he wants you to know he’s skeptical of your palette.  It’s enough to make your heart stand still and deaden your tastebuds.  Not for the faint of heart indeed.  It’s got four stars though, so somebody clearly likes this place.  And Japanese people seem to eat here, but perhaps they’re given a little more respect.  Overall though, I’m just not sure it’s the crowd who enjoys good Japanese food for it’s own sake.
Family style, authentic Japanese food made by a Japanese chef!
Great selection and fast service

We brought our kids (ages 7&9) and I was a little worried it wouldn't be "kid friendly". I couldn't have been more wrong. There were plenty of options on the menu for everyone to enjoy and we all thoroughly enjoyed our time here. We look forward to a return visit. I would recommend, though, if you're dining with kids to arrive as soon as the doors open (5pm). Seating is incredibly limited and by 6 there was sizable wait.

I can confidently say this is the best authentic Japanese food place to be! If you are interested in exploring not only sushi but other types of Izakaya (bar) style food. The price is just right for getting few bites or exploring variety with so many options for drinks. If you are looking purely sushi, then maybe visit west side of DC to Kotobuki. However, this is an amazing place with real Izakaya atmosphere!!!
I loved this place! We had such a fun time. Excellent food but not pretentious at all. Great spot if you want to try some Japanese food besides the standard fare.
A fun place to stop by but the food doesn't seem to be overly amazing. The octopus salad and tempura are great, sashimi just ok
Frequently changing and always exciting japanese cuisine.
Good food, cute and quiet restaurant. It's small, so not for large groups. We had 6 people which allowed us to make a reservation.
great food, amazing staff.
Great hot pot!
Good food, no wait when we came.
Fantastic Japanese food. Order the rice balls
Different than most sushi and to quality fish
Really awesome place. Just watching the chefs work from the counter seating is a treat. Delicious food from a professional staff in a traditional and relaxed atmosphere
Great dishes and best Sake collection!!
Well deserved legendary status. We got 7 items and all of them where 4/5+ stars. Great service. Come in early to avoid the wait.
Delicious sashimi and other small plates. Go for the specials and don't be afraid to step outside your comfort zone; the sea urchin was a special treat. It's all fantastic.
Decent Japanese food.  If you look for authenticity.  Limited seating so you might want to arrive early. Can get crowded and noisy but has lively ambience.

Service was good and atmosphere okay. First impressions were a quiet dining option in the heart of DC. Sat at a very cramped table with very uncomfortable seating for a party of 5. We were waited right away but service throughout the meal was somewhat slow. Drinks were refilled regularly. Yamazaki and Umeshu were great! Food was disappointing and overpriced, however. Portions were small, as well. Had multiple orders of the carpaccio, sashimi, short rib, tempura special, rice balls, Japanese omelet, octopus, squid, and fried shrimp... Some dishes were better than others; short ribs were disappointing as they were fatty with hardly any meat albeit flavorful. For the price and hype, I was expecting unparalleled Japanese cuisine. 3.5/5

Some of the food here is just superb! You'll never find better uni or beef tongue. And the assortment of grilled fish was wonderful. Even the omelet was surprisingly good. We would skip the sashimi, since it was just average, and the motsu skewer was nothing special. Lots to experiment with in terms of authentic Japanese shochu, local beers, and sake. A bit pricey, and it can get noisy, but we will definitely be back. Great service, too.
Delicious Japanese food
Food is pretty good but it's seriously overpriced, lacks atmosphere.
As close as I've come to Japan I believe. I know better places for Thai and that, but for a beer bar and restaurant it's the bomb. Always something I've never thought of or seen in DC

We came for a particular dish advertised in the Post, but they were out.  What food we did have was OK, but not exceptional.  The menu had a rather limited selection of things they specialize in, so do not expect as diverse a menu as other Japanese restaurants or sushi bars.

What an amazing place! You wouldn't think this place would have such great small plates by the unassuming exterior! The sashimi was perfect, the vegetables were eclectic, and the smoked amberjack was totally amazing!
Some items are a little pricey for what you get, but the foods is pretty solid all around

I liked the no-frills atmosphere to Seki a lot. Our server was very knowledgeable about the menu and very helpful in helping us craft our meal. It was just two of us, and we wanted to try everything but that seemed impossible. The sauteed shishito peppers (with crispy garlic) was amazing. It was also the best Japanese omelet I've ever had. The kara-age was great, and so was the eel and cucumber. We had a medium portion of the chef's selection of sashimi - and that was the most hit/miss dish of the evening. It was all really beautiful, and some of it was incredible and perfect, and some was not particularly enjoyable (but I think that was just a matter of personal preference). Rice balls were good too! We ended up getting sake that came in collectible glasses, so I took home two small glasses with pandas on them. We were pretty full by the end of the meal and could not entertain dessert, but next time I'd definitely try their flan and was very intrigued by both ginger and green tea ice cream (never had ginger ice cream and am pretty picky about green tea ice cream, but I'd believe theirs to be amazing).  Also I met my friend at about 6:15pm on a Wednesday after weeks of non-stop rain. He'd arrived about a half hour prior and said there was no wait. It was still pretty clear when I arrived and we were seated. It did pick up soon after.
Cosy Japanese with an interesting menu and a good selection of Japanese craft beers. Not cheap though.
Izakaya Seki is a Japanese small plate restaurant with excellent dishes. I recommend the tuna.
Walk-in only for groups smaller than 5
Great service, gives you a quick fix if you are craving Japanese
Kind of shocked how expensive it was for so little food.. Everything was good, but I don't want to pay $12 dollars for three one-inch pieces of eel...
Good sake menu and small, tasty dishes. If you pair sake with food be prepared to spend a few dollars

We came here on Saturday evening with some friends that have been here.  We had an initial 2 hours wait, which ended up being only 1 hour -- we were pretty pumped about it. We let our friends order since they were already familiarized with the menu.  The selection couldn't have been better... between sashimi, tempura special, fried pork belly, oysters and much other yummy food.  We went along with two bottles of sake that was simply delicious.  I would say this is probably one of the top Japanese restaurants in the area.  Service was just super!

There are not enough superlatives available to describe Izakaya Seki. Washington-ers should be thankful that such a wonderous representation of traditional Japanese cuisine is in their doorsteps. From the just-caught-fresh sashimi to their incredible udon, Izakaya Seki is an instant recommendation for anyone visiting the Washington area wanting to munch on delightful Japanese.

Was stoked to come here, once we actually sat down and ordered though, the plates were overpriced and tasted terrible, and not just one or two plates, the entire meal was genuinely unenjoyable.  Would not come back here, it wasn't worth the wait and price.
Good food. Get there for happy hour!
Tunanuta Scallions ! Amazing ! Best Jap food experience in DC. Pick up few dishes and share them it will be the best way to experience everything. Thank you.

Minimal digs is an understatement. I can't help but wonder if this place is trying too hard to be trendy and comes off condescending. Small plates were good to great, to bad. Some would say I have american taste- but they would be the condescendingly trendy ones- because I don't. Try this place for sure but, I want to like this place more than I do- and that's really the bottom line.

Having tried (and been slightly disappointed mostly) by many Japanese restaurants in DC I was pleasantly surprised how authentic and delicious the food is at this small izakaya tucked in on the quieter end of the neighborhood. The monkfish liver was especially memorable. It was fresh and buttery - not frozen and chewy like many other places. We also tried the fried chicken and two different kinda of onigiri - both delicious. The service was also on point - our server came to check on us regularly to see everything is. We had an early so the place wasn't too crowded. But I heard it gets very busy and the place could get filled up quickly. This has definitely been one of my better Japanese restaurant experiences in DC. I can't wait to come back and try other things on the menu.

Very intimate setting - the restaurant only has seating for about 10 people around the chef's station, but worth the wait.  The fish was delicious, fresh, and gorgeous.  Everything we tried was very good.  Not really a restaurant for people who are looking for a Westernized sushi experience; half the menu is in Japanese.  Bring a sense of adventure and you'll have some of the best sashimi and nigiri DC has to offer.
I really liked this cosy place. Like a little taste of Italy, except in this case, Japan.
Good with a group of people to maximize what you get to taste!

One of the most creative and authentic sushi place in town.  The place is small but cozy and prices are not that bad compared to Sushi Taro in Dupont.  I like the appetizers and anything grilled.  I heard they ship their fish from Japan and truck it in from Dulles every week...  V

Sushi Taro is still my favorite restaurant in DC but Izakaya Seki is a strong second.  They have really interesting things on the menu that isn't dumbed down for westerners.  If you're looking for a california roll you're at the wrong place.  Plus they have a real nice sake and sochu selection.
The Pork Belly is a must order, as well as the Mackerel.  Soba noodles in perfect dashi broth - well worth the price.
Amazing sashimi. Fried sardines and BBQ pork short ribs are also must-haves
Wonderful place - great food that is well-prepared, and a very friendly staff.
